Surprise was my first reaction to the gigantic menu of both American and Indian dishes at Tamber's where I hadn't eaten in at least 5 years. Delight was my reaction to the food. My companion and I took completely different roads. She opted for a New York Reuben sandwich which she claimed was a 5-star classic (delicious sauerkraut) as well as her french fries which were the best I have ever had in Baltimore. Crispy, not greasy at all, and flavorful!  My menu route went through Mumbai and I was completely impressed by my lamb saag (with really freshly done spinach!), a light and chewy garlic naan and a delightful mango lasse.  Even the long-grain rice was fragrant and tasty. Tamber's may well be one of Baltimore's best-kept secrets and I am not sorry I let the cat out of the bag! Try it!

Friday night, I ordered samosas and palak paneer for my family. We love samosas and palak paneer from Tambers, having ordered it many times before. While the samosas were perfect as always, the palak paneer was awful. The taste was intolerable and we all could not finish the dish. Understanding that this was uncharacteristic of Tambers and maybe it was just a bad batch, I called them to ask if we could get a replacement meal and that I would bring back the original palak paneer. The owner was rude, obnoxious, and OFFENSIVE to say the least. He said, "It will not taste like chicken wings or fish!" Then he proceeded to scold me about the health benefits of eating vegatarian meals. First, my family and I ARE VEGETARIANS and we all understand that a spinach-based dish would not taste like chicken or fish. Second, we have patronized Tambers for years because of their vegatarian options, especially the palak paneer which we LOVE and have only eaten from Tambers. We were unjustly profiled and that is UNACCEPTABLE. My family and I were completely taken aback with the conduct of the owner, who ended the conversation with, "If you don't like it, don't eat it!" We will NEVER patronize Tambers ever again!!

Tamber's is an interesting diner on the southeast corner of Johns Hopkins University's Homewood campus. Being a part of the Hopkins campus makes it a bit busy, especially during the school year, so expect a crowd and maybe a little bit of a wait.

One of my favorite places.  Looks like a diner, and the first half of the menu is diner food, but the second half is good authentic indian food. Reasonable prices, diverse enough menu that everyone can find something they like.
So awesome that you can get great basic Indian food alongside well-made classic diner fare. The portions of the Indian dishes are massive.

Service was quick. Food came to the table fast. 7/10 I would give it eight if my daughter didn't have to get up and ask for ice tea fill up, the restaurant wasn't even that busy.  Food was hot, but everything that we ordered taste the same. seen that in alot of Indian restaurants. I would happily pay $80.00 plus tip for food that would taste better, because of that i would say NOT GOOD VALUE as we didnt even order Appetizer or Desert!!!  Atmosphere can lighten up a little, place feels a little dark and stuffy.  Note to owner: 90% of the menu is American Diner, split personality Restaurants don't work. If people want a Burger they dont go to an Indian restaurant..Or am I getting some Indian food at an American style Diner.
